UML:TaggedValue.value: The LaboratoryAnlaysis-Specimen application schema extends the ISO19156 schema for Observations, Measurements and Sampling. It specifically describes processes and results related to the analysis of (geological) samples using instruments, most commonly in a laboratory environment. (Design of this package is based upon, and extends, the MOLES v3 data model.)
The LaboratoryAnalysis leaf package describes processes, instruments and result quality associated with quantitative analysis of samples.
The GeologicSpecimen package extends the ISO19156 O&M schema, and describes processes relevant to the sampling, preparation and analysis of geologic specimens.
Classes new in GeoSciML v3, or with significant change from GeoSciML v2.
A token is a simple string
Classes from other OGC or ISO schemas
GeoSciML v2 classes with no or only minor change in GeoSciML v3.
The LaboratoryAnalysis leaf package describes processes, instruments and result quality associated with quantitative analysis of samples.
Refers to a vocabulary of terms defining various instrument settings, such as voltage, current, vacuum, flow rates, etc

Suggest that gml:measure or swe:Quantity values are the most suitable format to deliver geochemistry results. Note that gml:measure is simpler because the "quality" part of swe:Quantity is not needed to deliver errors (errors are handled via AnalyticalSession-ResultQualityDescription).
Describes settings or parameters used in the operation of an analytical instrument (eg; voltage, current, vacuum)
Name of an instrument setting parameter used during an analytical session (eg, voltage, current, vacuum)
Value of an instrument setting (eg, 15 eV, 30 psi)
Instrument setting parameters may include voltage, current, vaccuum, flow rate, etc.
Concrete implementation of OM_Process. Links to an analytical session (data acquisition) or a computational process which produce analytical results.
Type of instrument used to perform an analytical observation
The category of instrument used in an analytical session (eg; XRF, ICPMS, SHRIMP, etc)
An optional text string to identify the model of instrument used. (eg instrument type = XRD, model = Siemens Diffraktometer D500)
An optional text string for the serial number of the machine used in an analytical session.
The date of the commissioning of an instrument (optional)
The location and owner of an instrument
Refers to a vocabulary of Instrument types (eg; XRF, ICPMS, SHRIMP, etc)
Describes the quality of analytical results acquired or calculated during an analytical process. This may include analytical errors, detection limits, quantitation limits, etc.
The name of the analyte for which the described result quality applies. Analytes may include elements, isotopes, and element or isotope ratios.

NameOfMeasure may include detection limit, quantitation limit, fractionation factor, and anlaytical errors for each analyte measured during an analytical session. Note: this attribute overrides the characterString attribute of the same name in DQ_QuantitativeAttributeAccuracy.

A calculation or computation process. This process step(s) may be applied to results from an AnalyticalSession in order to obtain result quality information or to adjust results values according to some conditions.
Refers to a vocabulary of analyte names
Name, and optional published citation, of the analytical method used in an analytical session
Name of analytical method used in a session (eg; XRF mass spectrometry, ICPMS, SHRIMP geochronology)
A published description of a particular analytical method (eg; a standard operating procedure document)
Refers to a vocabulary of terms describing the analytical method used in an analytical session (eg; XRF mass spectrometry, ICPMS, SHRIMP geochronology)
NameOfMeasure may include detection limit, quantitation limit, fractionation factor, and anlaytical errors for each analyte measured during an analytical session.

Reference specimens can be blanks and standard specimens that may be analysed in a machine session alongside unknown specimens. Citation refers to the published analytical information for a standard specimen.

This class describes the time and operator of a particular laboratory analytical session. AnalyticalSession also has associated links to the type of instrument and analytical method used, processing steps applied to data collected during a session, and instrument parameters unique to that session.
The time period during which the analysis was performed
The name of the operator or organisation responsible for the analytical session
Use gml:description for xlink:href URL to a photographic image. LA_Process = camera.
Method name examples: Atomic Absorption Spectroscopy, XRF, ICPMS, photo Use CI_Citation if there is formal documentation of the process
Instrument location for geochemical analyses is the laboratory the performed the analysis
Refers to a vocabulary of terms describing the type of quality measure (eg; detection limit, quantitation limit, analytical error, fractionation factor, etc)
A link to a group of specimens analysed during a particular instrument session (eg; a batch of specimens)
Use "parameter" to record things like ordering of Observations (if you cannot use resultTime), and other information not included under AnalyticalProcess.
The GeologicSpecimen package extends the ISO19156 O&M schema, and describes processes relevant to the sampling, preparation and analysis of geologic specimens.
eg: diamond drilling percussion drilling piston core drilling vibro core drilling channel sampling sea floor dredging geological hammer

Refers to a vocabulary of terms describing the samplingProcess used to obtain or create the Specimen. eg: diamond drilling percussion drilling piston core drilling vibro core drilling channel sampling sea floor dredging crushing mineral separation melting geological hammer
Implementation of SF_Process to describe sample preparation applied to geologic specimens, typically in preparation for analytical processes like geochemistry or microscopy.
Name of a method used in the preparation of a geologic specimen after sampling, but prior to analysis (eg, crushing, melting, acid digestion, mineral separation, thin sectioning)

Implementation of SF_Process to describe the method used to obtain a geologic specimen eg: diamond drilling percussion drilling piston core drilling vibro core drilling channel sampling sea floor dredging geological hammer

Name of the process used to obtain or create a geologic specimen. eg: diamond drilling percussion drilling piston core drilling vibro core drilling channel sampling sea floor dredging crushing mineral separation melting geological hammer

A reference specimen is a specimen with known or accepted values of some property. The mandatory citation property describes the location of a published description of these values. Reference specimens include analytical blanks.
Analytical results from a reference specimen analysed during an AnalyticalSession are delivered the same as the results of other specimens in that session.
Citation of published analytical results for this standard reference specimen
eg: crush mineral separation thin section cut polish mount acid digestion

Refers to a vocabulary of terms to describe sample preparation applied to geologic specimens, typically in preparation for analytical processes like geochemistry or microscopy. eg: crush mineral separation thin section cut polish mount acid digestion
